10 Tips and Tricks For Placement Interviews
What comes next when you finish your graduation? The ultimate goal is to get a handsome job to add more
charm to it, right? So, how you’re going to plan that? You might be good at studies and have successfully
achieved good grades in college, but that doesn’t mean that getting the job is just an easy-to-do task. Students
tend to lose confidence while going for placement interviews and end up with some horrible experiences.
Usually, at this stage, being nervous is so common, and getting placed is very significant for your success. So,
how you’re planning to do that?
Tips and Tricks for Interview
With the help of this article, we will understand
10 key tips and tricks for interviews that will help you with
placement interviews
. Let’s find out those tips one by one and the ways in which they can help you to crack your
interview.
1. “Mock Interview” is the Best Way to Start With
Being nervous is natural during interviews and to cope with this, it is advised to start preparing yourself from the
basics. One of the best methods is to do regular mock interviews. It will not only help you in building confidence
but will also help to crack down interviews easily. After all, it’s just about the psychological paradigm, the more
you practice, the more efficient it becomes, and in a matter of no time, you’ll realize that now you’re ready to
enter the real battle. You may start with the mock interviews by asking your friends or family members to actively
participate in this exercise but the best way is to visit the best source listed below to get a full-proof clean shot
for getting placed in an interview.
Complete Interview Preparation
gives you complete assistance on how to
prepare for the interview.

First Impression is the Last Impression
” and it does exist. Trust us, if you don’t have a
strong, crisp, and clear resume, then you’re out of the race for sure. Always make sure to add only and only

understand this, you’re presenting your resume, not any biography, and thus, the interview is only interested in
knowing what you’ve achieved so far, the skills that you possess, and the projects you’ve worked on, and maybe
a bit about you also. So, keep in mind these interview tips and tricks and make sure you’re not presenting 3-4

3. 360-Degree Analysis
First and foremost, what you must do before you begin is to gather as much information as possible about the
company you’re going to apply for or sit for the placement. The reason is, that the better homework you’ll do, the
more chances you’ll have of succeeding in the placement interview. There are likely chances that the recruiter
may ask you about the organization and especially about the job details that you’re appearing for so it’s better to
plan accordingly and gather as much information as possible such as its product/services, Year of establishment,
current CEO, CTO and the required job details that include qualifications and certifications. This will make your
impression in front of the employer that how serious are you about this job and will create more chances of you
getting hired.

4. Make “Problem-Solving Skills” Your Best Friend
During your graduation journey, it is a must to have the capability to cater to different kinds of complex questions
and should always be open up to take on new challenges. Likewise, companies also look for those potential
candidates who have deep knowledge and are ready to accept any technical puzzle in front of them. That’s why
problem-solving skills are a must to have while appearing for the placement interview. Today, companies like
TCS, Infosys, Accenture
, etc. who are among the biggest tech giants are also likely to pick those candidates who
can handle and solve complex queries and have the ability to adapt to any new challenge.
5. Stick with the Basics “Fundamental Topics”
You need to understand this so closely, no matter how hard you’re trying to get yourself placed in an interview,
you have to stick with the basics. Whether it’s the on-campus or off-campus placement arena, the first thing that
the interviewer is going to ask will start from the
data structure, basic programming language, code ethics
, and
maybe some part of system design, operating system, mathematics, and so on. However, you must’ve known this
after spending 4 years in graduation that being a CS/IT student, you have to stick around with these as long as
you can and mark these words, if you have the idea about these basics then nothing can stop you from getting
hired because companies want such candidates only.

7. Prepare “FAQ” Properly
There are certain scenarios where the recruiter may toss questions that can reflect your personality. That brings it
to light and understanding the importance of preparing those questions carefully. Questions such as “Strength”
and “Weakness” which is a very common questions too that can be asked for sure. What mistakes do people
generally do they focus on the strength part and they tend to ignore the weakness part which is also a crucial
part of the question. So, try to work on that part and answer all questions honestly because we all do have
weaknesses in ourselves so make sure to justify yourself positively.
8. Practice! Practice and Practice!
When you’re ready to appear for the interviews, keep that in mind, the basics, such as aptitude, mathematics, etc.
should be in practice throughout the time. Students generally focus on working on high-end problems and end
up missing the basic concepts of their core areas. This is the part where most of the companies target and they
set questions accordingly. So, ensure that you’re in touch with seniors and faculties to get insights about the
focus area to prepare for the placement interviews. Make sure you practice daily using our
practice
portal.
9. Be Honest!
Being honest is the best way to keep yourself up while stuck during an interview. Especially when you talk about
college placement, the employer will understand that you don’t have any prior experience, and being nervous is
also very common during that period. So, rather than molding things, if you’ll simply say that you don’t know,
that’ll surely work!
So, if you’re sure about something that you don’t know, say it rather than pretend that you do know. Let’s say the
interviewer asks about Python and you do have
knowledge of C#
, so just be clear and confront at that very
moment the same. That’s the only way of confronting and walking through those areas that are your interests
and might take you forward in getting hired. However, you may also consider some of the best resources while
preparing for the interview, let’s check them out.
